      },
      "lineNbr": 183,
      "author": {
        "id": 1118346
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-02T04:39:10Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yes, there might be more efficient way to collect output files written by services, but it\u0027s not easy.\n\nSome approaches I have considered:\n- Pulling files at the end of the test: this is tricky to support because a remote test might finish by hitting its timeout and there\u0027s no time left to pull files.\n- Pulling files asynchronously soon after gRPC calls: this is also difficult because we have to delay finishing a remote test while any pull is in flight.\n\nI don\u0027t say those approaches are impossible, but they need significant changes to the framework.\n\nWith the current synchronous approach, we can avoid problems mentioned above, scope of change is limited to the rpc package, and existing gRPC call performance is not affected because pull is not performed if no file is written to the output directory. So I think this is a good start. We can consider more efficient (and likely more complicated) approaches if it turns out that the performance is very bad.",
      "parentUuid": "8384e8f6_8675f031",
      "revId": "0e64f732710da00ae6e3dc046591abcd17201cf7",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba"
    },
